properties.title: Aquifer
properties.description:
Aquifer map for India generated with data from India Water Resources Information System (WRIS) ArcGIS portal. Ground water is the water present beneath the Earth’s surface in rock and soil pore spaces and in the fractures of rock formation. A unit of rock or an unconsolidated deposit is called an aquifer when it can yield a usable quantity of water. 

Based on the hydrogeological characteristics, the entire nation is divided into 14 principal aquifers: 

Alluvium
Laterite
Basalt
Sandstone
Shale
Limestone
Granite
Schist
Quartzite
Charnockite
Khondalite
Banded Gneissic Complex
Gneiss
Intrusive

Each major aquifer is uniquely identified by its region-specific aquifer properties such as aquifer thickness, specific yield, transmissivity and whether it is an unconfined and confined aquifer.
